484
00:22:05,637 --> 00:22:08,874
or something like this.

485
00:22:09,874 --> 00:22:13,244
<i>At 28,
we found Neil homeless,</i>

486
00:22:13,245 --> 00:22:16,414
<i>wandering around
the west coast of Scotland.</i>

487
00:22:16,415 --> 00:22:19,049
If the money runs out,
then for a few days,

488
00:22:19,050 --> 00:22:22,119
there's nowhere to go to
and that's all you can do.

489
00:22:22,120 --> 00:22:25,122
I simply have to find
the warmest shed I can find.

490
00:22:25,123 --> 00:22:29,993
<i>At 35, he was living
in a Council estate</i>

491
00:22:29,994 --> 00:22:32,495
<i>on the most northerly part
of Britain,</i>

492
00:22:32,496 --> 00:22:34,098
<i>the Shetland Islands.</i>

493
00:22:34,099 --> 00:22:38,202
And what would you like
to be doing, say in seven years?

494
00:22:38,203 --> 00:22:42,371
I can think of all kinds
of things I'd like to be doing.

495
00:22:42,372 --> 00:22:45,876
The real question is, what am I
likely to be doing?

496
00:22:45,877 --> 00:22:48,646
What are you likely
to be doing?

497
00:22:48,647 --> 00:22:50,581
That's a horrible question.

498
00:22:50,582 --> 00:22:51,814
Um...

499
00:22:51,815 --> 00:22:54,051
I tend to think the most likely
answer is that

500
00:22:54,052 --> 00:22:56,852
I'll be wandering homeless
around the streets of London.

501
00:23:01,025 --> 00:23:05,062
Can I just point out some of
the considerable disadvantages?

502
00:23:05,063 --> 00:23:06,764
First of all...

503
00:23:06,765 --> 00:23:09,766
<i>At 42, Neil had moved
to London</i>

504
00:23:09,767 --> 00:23:13,803
<i>and was a Liberal Democrat
on Hackney Council.</i>

505
00:23:13,804 --> 00:23:17,074
While I was in Shetland,
I felt very strongly

506
00:23:17,075 --> 00:23:19,042
that I should become
involved in politics.

507
00:23:19,043 --> 00:23:20,543
Simply because I felt

508
00:23:20,544 --> 00:23:23,112
I was not achieving anything
in the ways I really wanted to.

509
00:23:23,113 --> 00:23:27,350
<i>By 49, Neil had left London.</i>

510
00:23:27,351 --> 00:23:29,485
<i>Moved to Cumbria
in the northwest of England,</i>

511
00:23:29,486 --> 00:23:31,789
<i>and was a Liberal Democrat
member</i>

512
00:23:31,790 --> 00:23:33,658
<i>of his local district council.</i>

513
00:23:33,659 --> 00:23:37,828
It was a committee decision,
a majority decision.

514
00:23:37,829 --> 00:23:39,929
His own group on
the Establishment Committee

515
00:23:39,930 --> 00:23:41,532
agreed with the decision.

516
00:23:41,533 --> 00:23:43,700
Councilor Hughes?

517
00:23:43,701 --> 00:23:47,871
The Councilor Cook has
reconsidered his opinion

518
00:23:47,872 --> 00:23:50,674
he ventured at that meeting.

519
00:23:50,675 --> 00:23:54,977
Here we are in the center

520
00:23:54,978 --> 00:23:57,681
of the ward I represent
on the council.

521
00:23:57,682 --> 00:23:59,817
These are
our public toilets.

522
00:23:59,818 --> 00:24:04,187
I can assure you that no more
fierce battle has been fought,

523
00:24:04,188 --> 00:24:06,389
either on the playing fields
or indeed

524
00:24:06,390 --> 00:24:08,625
on the battlefields
of England, to save

525
00:24:08,626 --> 00:24:11,027
what might appear to be
a comparatively

526
00:24:11,028 --> 00:24:12,897
insignificant
local amenity.

527
00:24:12,898 --> 00:24:17,869
It sounds vaguely comic,
but presumably it's not to you.

528
00:24:17,870 --> 00:24:19,703
But when you live
in a small community,

529
00:24:19,704 --> 00:24:22,674
you become very proud,
rightly, of the facilities here.

530
00:24:22,675 --> 00:24:24,841
And people are willing to play
a part

531
00:24:24,842 --> 00:24:27,610
in helping to keep them going,
but they don't want

532
00:24:27,611 --> 00:24:30,380
to be ignored, they don't want
to be marginalized.

533
00:24:30,381 --> 00:24:33,484
My strength is being able
to keep going, really.

534
00:24:33,485 --> 00:24:35,352
My weakness is not being able

535
00:24:35,353 --> 00:24:37,920
to take any positive course
of action.

536
00:24:37,921 --> 00:24:41,492
No formal education can prepare
anybody for life.

537
00:24:41,493 --> 00:24:43,994
Only life can prepare you
for what comes.

538
00:24:43,995 --> 00:24:45,929
And sooner or later,
you're going

539
00:24:45,930 --> 00:24:47,931
to have to cross
certain barriers.

540
00:24:47,932 --> 00:24:51,601
There are a few things
I would like to say.

541
00:24:51,602 --> 00:24:54,571
And the first thing to say is,
there's been

542
00:24:54,572 --> 00:24:57,341
tremendous good will
toward the series.

543
00:24:57,342 --> 00:25:01,879
But I'm also aware that I'm
not the only participant

544
00:25:01,880 --> 00:25:06,449
who wants to set the record
straight in a number of ways.

545
00:25:06,450 --> 00:25:08,552
For so many millions of people,

546
00:25:08,553 --> 00:25:11,321
I'm here wearing my heart
on my sleeve.

547
00:25:11,322 --> 00:25:14,125
And they think they know
absolutely everything about me.

548
00:25:14,126 --> 00:25:16,994
There were countless people
writing me, saying,

549
00:25:16,995 --> 00:25:18,995
"I know exactly how
you feel."

550
00:25:18,996 --> 00:25:20,898
And actually,
from those letters,

551
00:25:20,899 --> 00:25:23,600
I would say none of them,
not a single one of them,

552
00:25:23,601 --> 00:25:25,402
knew exactly how
I was feeling.

553
00:25:25,403 --> 00:25:27,603
I've got a great deal of respect
for the Liberal Democrats,

554
00:25:27,604 --> 00:25:29,607
but I think that I won't
vote for them this time...

555
00:25:29,608 --> 00:25:33,476
Here in Cumbria,
I'm really glad to be doing

556
00:25:33,477 --> 00:25:36,045
what I do to be representing
people

557
00:25:36,046 --> 00:25:37,781
at local political level.

558
00:25:37,782 --> 00:25:40,217
But in one sense I'm doing that

559
00:25:40,218 --> 00:25:43,286
because it's the only way I've
been able to make any money.

560
00:25:43,287 --> 00:25:47,457
I get a derisory amount of money
for being a councilor.

561
00:25:47,458 --> 00:25:51,462
I do enjoy the work, but I've
been completely unsuccessful

562
00:25:51,463 --> 00:25:54,631
in trying to find a paid career
of any kind.

563
00:25:54,632 --> 00:26:00,036
I have always wanted to write
as a career

564
00:26:00,037 --> 00:26:03,740
and indeed have written
huge amounts.

565
00:26:03,741 --> 00:26:07,744
And ironically, despite
appearing in this program

566
00:26:07,745 --> 00:26:10,380
so frequently, nobody
has ever shown

567
00:26:10,381 --> 00:26:13,016
any serious interest in any
of the work I do.

568
00:26:13,017 --> 00:26:16,052
And believe me, it's a great
deal more important to me

569
00:26:16,053 --> 00:26:18,889
than anything I can say
on the television screen.

570
00:26:18,890 --> 00:26:21,825
Even if somebody sent it back
to me and said,

571
00:26:21,826 --> 00:26:24,829
"Well, I read it,
and it's rubbish, actually,"

572
00:26:24,830 --> 00:26:26,330
that would be very demoralizing,

573
00:26:26,331 --> 00:26:28,832
but at least some interaction
would have taken place.

574
00:26:28,833 --> 00:26:33,570
There's hardly a day goes by
when I don't write.

575
00:26:33,571 --> 00:26:36,373
That's a great gift,
isn't it?

576
00:26:36,374 --> 00:26:41,011
It is, but it shouldn't be
a sort of masturbation

577
00:26:41,012 --> 00:26:43,647
about which nobody else
knows anything.

578
00:26:43,648 --> 00:26:47,551
Neil Hughes is
the Liberal Democrat candidate.

579
00:26:47,552 --> 00:26:51,488
I and the Liberal Democrats want
to see a just and fair society.

580
00:26:51,489 --> 00:26:57,494
In 2006, I was invited to go to
Australia to give a talk,

581
00:26:57,495 --> 00:27:00,496
and the chap
who introduced me said,

582
00:27:00,497 --> 00:27:04,266
"Neil is clearly such a
profoundly motivated politician

583
00:27:04,267 --> 00:27:07,604
that we can all expect to see
him as Prime Minister

584
00:27:07,605 --> 00:27:09,139
of the United Kingdom."

585
00:27:09,140 --> 00:27:10,541
This wasn't a joke, I assure you

586
00:27:10,542 --> 00:27:12,341
he said this
with absolute seriousness.

587
00:27:12,342 --> 00:27:17,081
Now, it was ludicrous,
but this is how wildly skewed

588
00:27:17,082 --> 00:27:19,350
the perceptions have become.

589
00:27:19,351 --> 00:27:21,953
Do you think I would
really have been

590
00:27:21,954 --> 00:27:25,054
invited to Australia if they
were aware that I was someone

591
00:27:25,055 --> 00:27:28,024
who lives on a few quid a week
benefit and has

592
00:27:28,025 --> 00:27:31,195
as much chance of changing the
future of the United Kingdom

593
00:27:31,196 --> 00:27:33,363
as...

594
00:27:33,364 --> 00:27:35,898
I don't know,
someone who's serving

595
00:27:35,899 --> 00:27:37,634
a lifetime jail sentence?

596
00:27:43,976 --> 00:27:46,909
Yes, I'd say
I believed in God.

597
00:27:46,910 --> 00:27:48,978
Are you religious?

598
00:27:48,979 --> 00:27:52,183
Well, I go to church with
my parents on Sundays.

599
00:27:52,184 --> 00:27:55,585
I don't know even now whether I
do believe in God or not.

600
00:27:55,586 --> 00:27:58,389
I've thought an awful lot
about it, actually.

601
00:27:58,390 --> 00:27:59,689
And I still don't know.

602
00:27:59,690 --> 00:28:02,092
And how has he been
treating you?

603
00:28:03,593 --> 00:28:06,464
Well, I said to somebody last
week that I preferred

604
00:28:06,465 --> 00:28:08,764
the Old Testament
to the New Testament.

605
00:28:08,765 --> 00:28:13,169
Because in the Old Testament,
God is very unpredictable.

606
00:28:13,170 --> 00:28:18,507
And that's, I think,
how I've seen Him in my life.

607
00:28:18,508 --> 00:28:20,709
And Doreen as well...

608
00:28:20,710 --> 00:28:24,314
I was first a lay reader
in London.

609
00:28:24,315 --> 00:28:26,850
After completing
a little more training,

610
00:28:26,851 --> 00:28:29,520
I was relicensed by
the bishop of Carlisle.

611
00:28:29,521 --> 00:28:32,188
Well, good morning.

612
00:28:32,189 --> 00:28:34,791
Welcome to our service today.

613
00:28:34,792 --> 00:28:38,094
Just a couple of notices first.

614
00:28:38,095 --> 00:28:40,330
If you haven't already
been told,

615
00:28:40,331 --> 00:28:43,500
the proposed pet show
is, unfortunately, cancelled.

616
00:28:43,501 --> 00:28:45,769
I'm the lay minister.

617
00:28:45,770 --> 00:28:49,806
I'm licensed to carry out
quite a number of functions.

618
00:28:49,807 --> 00:28:55,079
That includes leading services, preaching,
taking part in the readings,

619
00:28:55,080 --> 00:28:57,380
helping to distribute
the communion, and so on.

620
00:28:57,381 --> 00:29:00,485
In fact, I can do more or less
everything a priest can do.

621
00:29:03,521 --> 00:29:08,492
To what extent
am I a good model for others?

622
00:29:08,493 --> 00:29:10,561
I don't know.
On the other hand,

623
00:29:10,562 --> 00:29:13,831
I am angry that so many doors
have been closed,

624
00:29:13,832 --> 00:29:16,667
not just for me,
but for so many people.

625
00:29:16,668 --> 00:29:18,968
I do feel nobody's
listening out there.

626
00:29:18,969 --> 00:29:21,271
There seem to be
few currents

627
00:29:21,272 --> 00:29:25,176
that are encouraging people to
stand up for their rights,

628
00:29:25,177 --> 00:29:27,977
not just their strict
legal rights,

629
00:29:27,978 --> 00:29:30,414
but their rights
to be human.

630
00:29:30,415 --> 00:29:35,418
In the name of the Father and of
the Son and of the Holy Spirit.

631
00:29:35,419 --> 00:29:39,590
I'm not unappreciative of
the honor it's been

632
00:29:39,591 --> 00:29:42,592
to be able to serve
the church,

633
00:29:42,593 --> 00:29:45,161
to be able
to serve my community,

634
00:29:45,162 --> 00:29:48,231
and I want to make that
absolutely clear.

635
00:29:48,232 --> 00:29:53,236
And it's true, I think it was Albert
Camus who said that life is what happens

636
00:29:53,237 --> 00:29:54,937
while you're waiting for
something else.

637
00:29:54,938 --> 00:29:58,475
But it's not the sort of place
where someone

638
00:29:58,476 --> 00:30:02,079
who wants to change society
is best employed.

639
00:30:02,080 --> 00:30:05,815
I would have thought
that was pretty obvious.

640
00:30:05,816 --> 00:30:09,753
In the winter, if you live in the country,
it was just all wet

641
00:30:09,754 --> 00:30:13,059
and there wouldn't be anything
for miles around.

642
00:30:15,059 --> 00:30:18,562
We're a very quiet village.

643
00:30:18,563 --> 00:30:21,732
There's always room for more
activity and for more people

644
00:30:21,733 --> 00:30:24,167
being involved, but I think
we do fairly well

645
00:30:24,168 --> 00:30:27,571
as a diversity of groups.

646
00:30:27,572 --> 00:30:31,007
They're still trying to
persuade me to go in.

647
00:30:31,008 --> 00:30:33,577
Apparently Alan has cried off
at the last minute,

648
00:30:33,578 --> 00:30:35,012
so there's just
the two of them.

649
00:30:35,013 --> 00:30:38,148
I think it was Pascal, the great
philosopher and mathematician,

650
00:30:38,149 --> 00:30:42,285
who said that if a man can live
happily in his own living room

651
00:30:42,286 --> 00:30:46,022
most of his life, then he's achieved
the utmost philosophical breakthrough,

652
00:30:46,023 --> 00:30:48,291
and philosophically speaking,
that's true, but I can't.

653
00:30:48,292 --> 00:30:50,460
You stick me in my living room
for one hour on my own

654
00:30:50,461 --> 00:30:52,395
and I want to be out
doing something.

655
00:30:52,396 --> 00:30:54,130
I want to be out
changing things.

656
00:30:54,131 --> 00:30:58,002
I have always had
a nervous complaint.

657
00:30:58,003 --> 00:31:00,637
I've had it since I was 16.

658
00:31:00,638 --> 00:31:03,306
It was responsible for my
leaving university

659
00:31:03,307 --> 00:31:05,876
and for some of my difficulties
with work.

660
00:31:05,877 --> 00:31:08,245
Do you worry about
your sanity?

661
00:31:11,182 --> 00:31:12,716
Um...

662
00:31:12,717 --> 00:31:15,652
Other people sometimes
worry about it.

663
00:31:15,653 --> 00:31:17,323
Like who?

664
00:31:20,323 --> 00:31:24,227
As I said, I sometimes can

665
00:31:24,228 --> 00:31:26,463
be found behaving in...

666
00:31:26,464 --> 00:31:28,631
in an erratic fashion.

667
00:31:28,632 --> 00:31:30,734
Sometimes I get very frustrated.

668
00:31:30,735 --> 00:31:32,136
Very angry.

669
00:31:32,137 --> 00:31:33,603
For no apparent reason.

670
00:31:33,604 --> 00:31:36,473
For a reason which won't be apparent
to other people around me.

671
00:31:36,474 --> 00:31:38,140
I don't see any way out.

672
00:31:38,141 --> 00:31:41,145
I've thought of everything
I possibly could.

673
00:31:41,146 --> 00:31:43,947
It seemed to me for a long time
that getting a reliable job

674
00:31:43,948 --> 00:31:46,248
and a nice place to live
would be the solution.

675
00:31:46,249 --> 00:31:47,485
Well, I haven't succeeded.

676
00:31:47,486 --> 00:31:51,321
I can't see any immediate future
at all.

677
00:31:51,322 --> 00:31:52,956
Although there have been times

678
00:31:52,957 --> 00:31:54,991
in my life
when I've been suicidal,

679
00:31:54,992 --> 00:31:57,861
that wasn't one of them.

680
00:31:57,862 --> 00:32:00,996
So there have been
worse than...

681
00:32:00,997 --> 00:32:03,233
Yes, but it's not for
this program

682
00:32:03,234 --> 00:32:05,034
to expose my private feelings,

683
00:32:05,035 --> 00:32:07,170
and yet many people feel
it has.

684
00:32:07,171 --> 00:32:08,871
Ultimately.

685
00:32:08,872 --> 00:32:12,575
Although this time round,
I've been far more candid

686
00:32:12,576 --> 00:32:17,051
than I perhaps ever have
in the past.

687
00:32:20,051 --> 00:32:24,287
My formal contact with
the psychiatric establishment

688
00:32:24,288 --> 00:32:29,591
belongs mostly to my mid
and later teens

689
00:32:29,592 --> 00:32:32,027
and a short period
of my early 20s.

690
00:32:32,028 --> 00:32:35,098
But I soon came
to the opinion

691
00:32:35,099 --> 00:32:38,569
that I could help myself
far better

692
00:32:38,570 --> 00:32:42,571
than those who were
purporting to help me.

693
00:32:42,572 --> 00:32:46,543
But I was aware even then that a
lot of the therapeutic technique

694
00:32:46,544 --> 00:32:49,780
is about leading people
to exactly this conclusion,

695
00:32:49,781 --> 00:32:51,447
if it's done well.

696
00:32:51,448 --> 00:32:54,650
So I'm not going down the line
of criticizing

697
00:32:54,651 --> 00:32:56,485
the medical establishment.

698
00:32:56,486 --> 00:33:01,992
But did you refuse to go
into any sort of treatment?

699
00:33:01,993 --> 00:33:07,063
No, I did have contact.

700
00:33:07,064 --> 00:33:09,933
But then you
discontinued it.

701
00:33:09,934 --> 00:33:11,601
Yes.

702
00:33:11,602 --> 00:33:14,638
Do you still think
that was wise?

703
00:33:14,639 --> 00:33:17,713
Yes.

704
00:33:21,713 --> 00:33:24,348
Are you scared
of getting old?

705
00:33:24,349 --> 00:33:26,950
Yeah, I don't want to live
to be that old.

706
00:33:26,951 --> 00:33:29,186
I think if I can reach
something like 70

707
00:33:29,187 --> 00:33:30,652
or 75 in reasonable health,

708
00:33:30,653 --> 00:33:32,525
that will be quite enough
for me.

709
00:33:34,525 --> 00:33:36,493
When I get married,

710
00:33:36,494 --> 00:33:38,629
I don't want to have
any children,

711
00:33:38,630 --> 00:33:42,565
because they're always doing
naughty things

712
00:33:42,566 --> 00:33:45,835
and making
the whole house untidy.

713
00:33:45,836 --> 00:33:52,141
I always told myself that I
would never have children.

714
00:33:52,142 --> 00:33:54,311
Why?

715
00:33:54,312 --> 00:33:57,414
Because...

716
00:33:57,415 --> 00:34:01,651
Well, because children inherit
something from their parents.

717
00:34:01,652 --> 00:34:05,688
And even if my wife were
the most high-spirited

718
00:34:05,689 --> 00:34:08,257
and ordinary and normal
of people,

719
00:34:08,258 --> 00:34:11,561
the child would still stand
a very fair chance

720
00:34:11,562 --> 00:34:16,199
of being not totally full
of happiness

721
00:34:16,200 --> 00:34:19,769
because of what he or she will
have inherited from me.

722
00:34:19,770 --> 00:34:22,339
Have you ever really had

723
00:34:22,340 --> 00:34:25,375
a romantic emotional
relationship?

724
00:34:25,376 --> 00:34:27,677
Oh, I've had several,

725
00:34:27,678 --> 00:34:31,415
but the fact that I'm living
alone still

726
00:34:31,416 --> 00:34:35,755
obviously betrays the fact that
none of them has endured.

727
00:34:37,755 --> 00:34:41,890
Is there a reason
for that?

728
00:34:41,891 --> 00:34:47,164
Relationships always involve
two people.

729
00:34:47,165 --> 00:34:49,733
