00:59:47,996 --> 00:59:51,934
I left school when I was 16.
I went to Paris.

1215
00:59:51,935 --> 00:59:55,370
I went to secretarial college
and got a job.

1216
00:59:55,371 --> 00:59:59,274
What made you decide to
leave school and go to Paris?

1217
00:59:59,275 --> 01:00:02,144
Well, I just wasn't interested
in school

1218
01:00:02,145 --> 01:00:04,079
and just wanted to get away.

1219
01:00:04,080 --> 01:00:05,914
If you had had no choice

1220
01:00:05,915 --> 01:00:09,151
but to get out there and support
yourself,

1221
01:00:09,152 --> 01:00:10,885
the chances would
have been greater

1222
01:00:10,886 --> 01:00:13,021
that you would have forced
yourself to do it.

1223
01:00:13,022 --> 01:00:17,024
Yeah, that's possibly true,
but at the age of...

1224
01:00:17,025 --> 01:00:20,863
11, 12, 13, are you really
aware of that?

1225
01:00:20,864 --> 01:00:24,265
Now, that's
a very telling question.

1226
01:00:24,266 --> 01:00:27,102
In my world, you betcha.

1227
01:00:27,103 --> 01:00:30,405
When I grow up,
I'd like to find out

1228
01:00:30,406 --> 01:00:33,140
all about the moon and all that.

1229
01:00:33,141 --> 01:00:35,510
And I said I was interested
in physics and chemistry,

1230
01:00:35,511 --> 01:00:37,012
I'm not going
to do that here.

1231
01:00:37,013 --> 01:00:40,649
<i>At 14, Nick was away
at boarding school.</i>

1232
01:00:40,650 --> 01:00:42,400
<i>At 21, reading physics
at Oxford.</i>

1233
01:00:43,987 --> 01:00:48,456
<i>His road to Oxford started
in a one-room village school.</i>

1234
01:00:48,457 --> 01:00:49,858
My father was here.

1235
01:00:49,859 --> 01:00:52,126
A long time ago, he must be
somewhere in these pictures.

1236
01:00:52,127 --> 01:00:54,863
I remember distinctly
coming here one day

1237
01:00:54,864 --> 01:00:57,566
and I'd missed a day
for some reason

1238
01:00:57,567 --> 01:01:00,702
and they'd been talking about
something to do with aeroplanes.

1239
01:01:00,703 --> 01:01:02,903
And the teacher said,
"We missed you

1240
01:01:02,904 --> 01:01:05,640
because you would have known
about aeroplanes."

1241
01:01:05,641 --> 01:01:08,376
I knew nothing about aeroplanes,
but I thought,

1242
01:01:08,377 --> 01:01:10,579
"Oh, I know about aeroplanes,
do I?"

1243
01:01:10,580 --> 01:01:13,381
So then I went off
and read about aeroplanes.

1244
01:01:13,382 --> 01:01:15,850
That could easily have been
the start of,

1245
01:01:15,851 --> 01:01:17,619
"I want to go
to the moon."

1246
01:01:17,620 --> 01:01:19,821
I think she planted
that idea in me.

1247
01:01:19,822 --> 01:01:22,395
Do you have
a girlfriend?

1248
01:01:25,395 --> 01:01:28,097
I don't want to answer that.

1249
01:01:28,098 --> 01:01:32,700
I don't want to answer
those kind of questions.

1250
01:01:32,701 --> 01:01:35,771
I thought that one would
come up,

1251
01:01:35,772 --> 01:01:39,173
because when I was doing
the other one, somebody said,

1252
01:01:39,174 --> 01:01:41,443
"What do you think about girls?"

1253
01:01:41,444 --> 01:01:43,378
And I said, "I don't answer
questions like that."

1254
01:01:43,379 --> 01:01:44,878
Is that the reason
you're asking it?

1255
01:01:44,879 --> 01:01:47,082
The best answer would be to say

1256
01:01:47,083 --> 01:01:50,084
that I don't answer questions
like that.

1257
01:01:50,085 --> 01:01:52,820
You know, it was what I said
when I was 7,

1258
01:01:52,821 --> 01:01:55,090
and it's still
the most sensible,

1259
01:01:55,091 --> 01:01:57,425
but what about them?

1260
01:01:57,426 --> 01:02:01,896
If you'd been somebody who
had had fixed ideas

1261
01:02:01,897 --> 01:02:04,566
of a woman's role in marriage
that meant

1262
01:02:04,567 --> 01:02:07,468
dinner on the table
at 6:00 every evening...

1263
01:02:07,469 --> 01:02:09,671
Didn't I tell you
about that?

1264
01:02:09,672 --> 01:02:14,943
<i>By 28, Nick had married Jackie,
a fellow student from Oxford.</i>

1265
01:02:14,944 --> 01:02:19,414
<i>They had a son, Adam.
By 42, they were divorced.</i>

1266
01:02:19,415 --> 01:02:21,849
What I've concluded, and
I've talked to other people

1267
01:02:21,850 --> 01:02:23,485
about this
who've gone through it...

1268
01:02:23,486 --> 01:02:27,055
I'm not sure if they feel it as strongly
as I did, but it was like a death.

1269
01:02:27,056 --> 01:02:30,524
Anything could happen.
We could easily drift apart.

1270
01:02:30,525 --> 01:02:32,260
There are so many pressures...

1271
01:02:32,261 --> 01:02:35,329
If your spouse died,
you could look back and think,

1272
01:02:35,330 --> 01:02:37,999
"well, it was wonderful
while it lasted."

1273
01:02:38,000 --> 01:02:42,936
But in a divorce,
you can't look back and say,

1274
01:02:42,937 --> 01:02:44,939
"these are all happy memories."

1275
01:02:44,940 --> 01:02:47,041
Hey!

1276
01:02:47,042 --> 01:02:52,347
Cryss is my new wife.

1277
01:02:52,348 --> 01:02:55,249
I don't mean to be superficial,
but I think

1278
01:02:55,250 --> 01:02:58,320
she's the most beautiful woman
I've ever seen.

1279
01:02:58,321 --> 01:03:00,055
Is he sexy?

1280
01:03:00,056 --> 01:03:01,223
Oh, man.

1281
01:03:03,359 --> 01:03:07,561
Absolutely.

1282
01:03:07,562 --> 01:03:11,032
Didn't you have fun
with that one?

1283
01:03:11,033 --> 01:03:14,736
I always need to learn
patience and...

1284
01:03:14,737 --> 01:03:17,037
What do I need to learn?

1285
01:03:17,038 --> 01:03:18,840
Shall I get out my list?

1286
01:03:18,841 --> 01:03:20,575
Yeah, we need the list.

1287
01:03:20,576 --> 01:03:22,044
Go on.

1288
01:03:22,045 --> 01:03:23,378
Um...

1289
01:03:23,379 --> 01:03:27,615
Tell me, do you have
any boyfriends, Suzy?

1290
01:03:27,616 --> 01:03:29,249
Um...

1291
01:03:29,250 --> 01:03:30,485
Yes.

1292
01:03:30,486 --> 01:03:32,620
Tell me about him.

1293
01:03:32,621 --> 01:03:34,923
But he lives off in Scotland

1294
01:03:34,924 --> 01:03:38,360
and I think he's 13.

1295
01:03:38,361 --> 01:03:41,699
Have you got
any boyfriends, Suzy?

1296
01:03:43,699 --> 01:03:48,975
What is your attitude
towards marriage for yourself?

1297
01:03:52,975 --> 01:03:55,077
I haven't given it
a lot of thought,

1298
01:03:55,078 --> 01:03:57,378
because I'm very, very
cynical about it.

1299
01:03:57,379 --> 01:04:00,849
When I last saw you
at 21, you were nervous,

1300
01:04:00,850 --> 01:04:03,751
you were chain-smoking,
you were uptight,

1301
01:04:03,752 --> 01:04:05,385
and now you seem happy?

1302
01:04:05,386 --> 01:04:08,856
What's happened to you over
these last seven years?

1303
01:04:08,857 --> 01:04:11,425
I suppose Rupert.

1304
01:04:11,426 --> 01:04:13,428
I'll give you some credit.

1305
01:04:13,429 --> 01:04:17,664
I'm now chain-smoking.

1306
01:04:17,665 --> 01:04:22,503
I think you can't just walk
through a marriage

1307
01:04:22,504 --> 01:04:25,340
and think once you get married,
it's all going to be

1308
01:04:25,341 --> 01:04:26,907
roses and everything forever.

1309
01:04:26,908 --> 01:04:29,678
It's very hard to actually say
what it is

1310
01:04:29,679 --> 01:04:32,314
that goes on
between a couple.

1311
01:04:32,315 --> 01:04:35,115
It's either there
or it's not.

1312
01:04:35,116 --> 01:04:38,720
Any marriage
has its ups and downs.

1313
01:04:38,721 --> 01:04:42,157
But somehow,
whether it's through luck

1314
01:04:42,158 --> 01:04:46,593
or determination, we've
worked through

1315
01:04:46,594 --> 01:04:48,600
the difficult times.

1316
01:04:53,803 --> 01:04:58,039
One of my favorite
places in Oxford,

1317
01:04:58,040 --> 01:05:01,075
Merton Chapel.

1318
01:05:01,076 --> 01:05:03,678
Here's this lovely top part
of the cross.

1319
01:05:03,679 --> 01:05:07,782
And there was going to be
the main part of the cross.

1320
01:05:07,783 --> 01:05:10,117
This is one of the places
in England

1321
01:05:10,118 --> 01:05:12,620
that just is tremendously
important to me.

1322
01:05:12,621 --> 01:05:15,390
After I left the Dales,
this was where I spent

1323
01:05:15,391 --> 01:05:18,227
the next six years,
and then I went to America.

1324
01:05:18,228 --> 01:05:22,229
Look, isn't this beautiful?
This is Mob Quad.

1325
01:05:22,230 --> 01:05:24,932
I believe that it's
a historical fact

1326
01:05:24,933 --> 01:05:29,003
that quite a lot students were
massacred in the middle ages.

1327
01:05:29,004 --> 01:05:31,840
When I came here, I thought I'd
died and gone to heaven.

1328
01:05:31,841 --> 01:05:33,274
But I was under an awful lot

1329
01:05:33,275 --> 01:05:35,778
of stress
all the time I was here

1330
01:05:35,779 --> 01:05:38,680
trying to succeed in this place
as well.

1331
01:05:38,681 --> 01:05:42,416
So this was my staircase
in my first year

1332
01:05:42,417 --> 01:05:44,751
and also in my third year.

1333
01:05:44,752 --> 01:05:47,756
There was this fellow
who lived in the room nextdoor to me

1334
01:05:47,757 --> 01:05:49,457
and he came in one day
to tell me some story.

1335
01:05:49,458 --> 01:05:51,892
And on his way out, he said, "Do you know,

1336
01:05:51,893 --> 01:05:55,329
I don't associate intelligence
with your accent."

1337
01:05:55,330 --> 01:05:57,399
It would seem really ridiculous

1338
01:05:57,400 --> 01:06:00,568
to any of my friends
who watch this if I said,

1339
01:06:00,569 --> 01:06:03,037
"Christ, aren't I
a great success?

1340
01:06:03,038 --> 01:06:04,039
Look at me!"

1341
01:06:04,040 --> 01:06:05,807
You know, what success?

1342
01:06:05,808 --> 01:06:10,945
<i>By the time he was 28,
Nick had emigrated to America.</i>

1343
01:06:10,946 --> 01:06:13,814
<i>He was doing research
into nuclear fusion</i>

1344
01:06:13,815 --> 01:06:18,019
<i>at the University
of Wisconsin.</i>

1345
01:06:18,020 --> 01:06:20,155
If you'd been offered

1346
01:06:20,156 --> 01:06:22,957
a similar type of job
over here...

1347
01:06:22,958 --> 01:06:25,459
In a heartbeat.

1348
01:06:25,460 --> 01:06:27,361
You would have stayed.

1349
01:06:27,362 --> 01:06:28,762
In a heartbeat.

1350
01:06:28,763 --> 01:06:33,168
I mean, I dreamed of getting
a university job over here.

1351
01:06:33,169 --> 01:06:36,905
Maggie Thatcher was squeezing
the universities

1352
01:06:36,906 --> 01:06:40,175
like crazy at that very moment
in time.

1353
01:06:40,176 --> 01:06:43,778
And it was the worst time to be
working in a university

1354
01:06:43,779 --> 01:06:45,379
in generations.

1355
01:06:45,380 --> 01:06:48,582
England doesn't seem
to concern itself

1356
01:06:48,583 --> 01:06:52,820
with training people like me
and wanting them around.

1357
01:06:52,821 --> 01:06:56,091
There doesn't seem to be
a sense of urgency

1358
01:06:56,092 --> 01:06:59,994
or a strong will to have people
developing technology

1359
01:06:59,995 --> 01:07:02,530
to help keep the country going.

1360
01:07:02,531 --> 01:07:05,700
The fusion reaction
gives off energy and produces

1361
01:07:05,701 --> 01:07:08,870
the power that would
be turned into electrical...

1362
01:07:08,871 --> 01:07:11,338
I was on a mission, you know,

1363
01:07:11,339 --> 01:07:15,577
to get extremely cheap, clean,
plentiful electricity.

1364
01:07:15,578 --> 01:07:18,479
So nuclear fusion looked like
it was going to do that.

1365
01:07:18,480 --> 01:07:21,550
But even then, they were saying
"it's 20 years away."

1366
01:07:21,551 --> 01:07:25,220
I would say absolutely not
in my lifetime.

1367
01:07:25,221 --> 01:07:28,122
It was kind of heartbreaking.

1368
01:07:28,123 --> 01:07:32,260
So I had to find
something else to do.

1369
01:07:32,261 --> 01:07:36,331
So the area that I'm looking at
is this times this.

1370
01:07:36,332 --> 01:07:39,133
When I go into a classroom
full of undergraduates,

1371
01:07:39,134 --> 01:07:41,702
I try and explain to them
why they might want

1372
01:07:41,703 --> 01:07:43,470
to try and do it.

1373
01:07:43,471 --> 01:07:45,439
That's my attempt to open
a little door for them.

1374
01:07:45,440 --> 01:07:51,512
<i>Nick is a professor
of electrical engineering.</i>

1375
01:07:51,513 --> 01:07:54,048
My ambition as a scientist
is to be

1376
01:07:54,049 --> 01:07:56,617
more famous for doing science
than for being in this film.

1377
01:07:56,618 --> 01:07:59,068
Unfortunately, Michael,
it's not going to happen.

1378
01:08:02,190 --> 01:08:04,763
When I get married,
I'd like to have two children.

1379
01:08:07,763 --> 01:08:10,865
I'm not very
children-minded at the moment.

1380
01:08:10,866 --> 01:08:14,102
I don't know
if I ever will be.

1381
01:08:14,103 --> 01:08:16,303
What do you think
about them?

1382
01:08:16,304 --> 01:08:18,372
Well, I don't like babies.

1383
01:08:18,373 --> 01:08:24,646
<i>At 28, Suzy had two sons...
Thomas and Oliver.</i>

1384
01:08:24,647 --> 01:08:26,180
Come catch it.

1385
01:08:26,181 --> 01:08:30,419
<i>By the time she was 35, she
also had a daughter, Laura.</i>

1386
01:08:30,420 --> 01:08:33,655
Mummy? Laura wants you.

1387
01:08:33,656 --> 01:08:36,090
We were lucky.

1388
01:08:36,091 --> 01:08:41,495
We had a very good family unit
with them growing up.

1389
01:08:41,496 --> 01:08:43,331
And that meant an awful lot
to me,

1390
01:08:43,332 --> 01:08:45,265
that I was able to do that
for them,

1391
01:08:45,266 --> 01:08:47,068
'cause I never had it
for myself.

1392
01:08:47,069 --> 01:08:50,003
And you've done it, you've been
tremendously successful at it.

1393
01:08:50,004 --> 01:08:52,274
Well, see, that's my problem.

1394
01:08:52,275 --> 01:08:55,242
I don't think of myself
as being...

1395
01:08:55,243 --> 01:08:58,846
I just do my best and do
what I can for them.

1396
01:09:01,217 --> 01:09:02,650
Did all your children

1397
01:09:02,651 --> 01:09:04,752
go to university
or your daughter did?

1398
01:09:04,753 --> 01:09:08,957
Yes, and my son did,
the eldest one.

1399
01:09:08,958 --> 01:09:10,958
Hello.

1400
01:09:10,959 --> 01:09:15,596
I haven't had a successful
career, but I do feel fulfilled.